## Looking Back From the Other Side

Day 97 closed the capstone — the second-year priority agenda, the honest lessons, and the final note that the next step is not Day 98 but executing the work. I meant that. The specificity discipline, the POA&M accountability system, the monitoring-as-assurance versus monitoring-as-detection distinction — those are not reflections that exist only in writing. They are the operational habits the last 97 days have built.

But Day 98 is worth its own entry, because looking back at the full arc of this project from the beginning reveals something that is hard to see while you are in the middle of it: the learning does not happen in a straight line. There are days when a single concept lands with clarity that reorganizes everything you understood before it. There are days when a finding from the monitoring program retroactively makes a control implementation choice from forty days earlier make more sense. There are days — I will be honest — when the task feels like compliance theater until you connect it to a real breach, a real patient, a real organizational consequence.

Day 98 is a course recap in the genuine sense: not a summary of what each day covered, but a reflection on how the learning accumulated and what the full journey reveals about what GRC work actually is.

---

## The Three Phases of the Journey — What Each Phase Taught

---

### Phase 1: Days 1–45 — Learning to See the System

The first phase of the project was about developing the ability to see the OpenMRS system as a security problem — not just a technical deployment but an information system with a boundary, a mission context, a patient population, a regulatory environment, and a risk profile that reflects all of those things together.

Days 1 through 10 established the foundational GRC concepts — governance, risk, compliance as separate disciplines that the RMF integrates. This felt abstract at the time. The abstraction became concrete when FIPS 199 categorization arrived in Day 44 and required a judgment call: is the confidentiality impact HIGH or MODERATE for a system that stores HIV status and mental health records for a population where disclosure could cause social harm, employment discrimination, and physical danger? The categorization exercise forced a connection between the regulatory framework (FIPS 199 definitions) and the real-world consequences for real patients that the security program exists to prevent.

The asset inventory (Day 33), system boundary (Day 34), information types (Day 35), and data flows (Day 36) were technical exercises that produced something more than technical outputs — they produced a precise picture of what the security program was protecting and why each component mattered. The EC2 instance matters because it runs the application that clinical staff use to dispense antiretroviral therapy to HIV/AIDS patients. The RDS instance matters because it stores the medication history that prevents dangerous drug interactions. The S3 backup matters because it is the recovery path when everything else fails.

This is the first thing the full journey taught me: **GRC starts with understanding what you are protecting and why it matters to the people who depend on it.** Not controls. Not frameworks. Not compliance requirements. The mission, the people, the data, and the consequences of failure.

---

### Phase 2: Days 46–75 — Building the Program and Learning That Controls Are Commitments

The second phase was the construction phase — selecting controls, documenting them in the SSP, preparing for and surviving the formal assessment, receiving the conditional ATO, and executing the Monitor step. This is where the volume of GRC work is concentrated, and it is where the gap between knowing what a control is and implementing it at operational depth becomes real.

Several days in this phase produced insights I did not anticipate.

**Day 52 (Continuous Monitoring Strategy):** The moment I understood that the formal assessment is a snapshot and the monitoring program is what makes the snapshot meaningful over time. A system that was assessed as compliant at authorization but has no monitoring program may have drifted significantly by re-authorization. The monitoring program is not the follow-up to the real work — it is the mechanism that keeps the real work relevant.

**Day 65 (POA&M Development):** The moment I understood that the POA&M is not a list of failures — it is a governance instrument. An organization that has a POA&M with documented items, milestone plans, and closing evidence is demonstrating that it has found gaps and is managing them. An organization with no POA&M items is either perfect (impossible) or not looking (likely). The POA&M is how you prove the security program is honest.

**Day 66 (Risk Response Decisions):** The moment I understood that formal risk acceptance is a legitimate governance outcome, not a failure to remediate. Not every finding can be patched within 30 days. Some findings require organizational decisions about residual risk that involve authorities beyond the ISSO. The ISSO's job is to characterize the risk accurately, present the options, and ensure the acceptance decision is made at the right level with documented rationale. Accepting a risk is not the same as ignoring it.

**Day 72 (SSP Updates and M-4):** The moment I understood that the SSP is a living document — not the finished product of the preparation phase but the continuously maintained record of what the system's security posture actually is. SSP v1.2 reflects operational learning that the initial implementation could not have anticipated. Every SSP update is evidence that the monitoring program is producing useful information.

This is the second thing the full journey taught me: **Controls are commitments, not configurations.** Implementing MFA is not a compliance achievement — it is a promise that unauthorized access requires more than a stolen password. Maintaining that promise over time, through personnel changes and software updates and configuration drift, is the actual security work. The monitoring program is what keeps the commitments real.

---

### Phase 3: Days 76–97 — Governance Foundations and the Capstone Synthesis

The third phase was the governance foundations and capstone synthesis — policy writing, AWS automation, POA&M management, compliance checklists, audit readiness, incident response, third-party risk, metrics, dashboards, stakeholder communication, and then the twelve-day capstone that organized everything into a coherent program document.

The governance foundations phase produced something I did not fully anticipate: a clear picture of the difference between technical security and organizational security.

Technical security is about whether the controls are correctly configured. Does the S3 bucket have Block Public Access enabled? Does the IAM password policy meet the complexity requirements? Is CloudTrail enabled with log file validation? These are answerable with Config rules and automated monitoring.

Organizational security is about whether the organization's culture, processes, and governance structures support the controls over time. Does the IT Administrator treat the CM-3 change management process as obligatory or optional? Does clinical leadership understand the contingency plan well enough to invoke it at 2am? Does the staff member who receives a suspicious email know what to do — and does she do it under realistic conditions, not just in a training module?

The M-002 finding (unauthorized IAM password policy change), the A-7 finding (IAM entity creation without notification), the M-004 finding (over-privilege from role change without ISSO notification), and the CP-3 retention gap all pointed to the same organizational security challenge: the technical controls were correctly implemented, and the human processes that support those controls needed development.

The capstone synthesis made this pattern visible in a way that the individual daily entries could not — looking at all seven monitoring findings together reveals that five of them were process compliance or communication failures, not technical failures. This is the integrated view that the capstone's synthesis goal was designed to produce.

This is the third thing the full journey taught me: **Technical security and organizational security require different interventions.** Technical gaps close with patches and configuration changes. Organizational gaps close through policy acknowledgment, training behavioral reinforcement, and the accumulated experience of a monitoring program that makes the gap visible enough that the organization treats it as a genuine priority.

