## The Real-World Cases That Grounded the Learning

One of the design choices for this project was always using verified, interview-ready real-world cases rather than generic examples. Looking back at the full list, a few cases deserve recognition for how much conceptual work they did:

**Target breach (2013):** Access reviews that confirmed employment rather than role accuracy — the exact failure mode that the M-004 quarterly access review template update was designed to prevent. The Target case is why the access review template change matters.

**Log4Shell (2021):** Organizations with complete dependency inventories responded faster than those without. The monthly OWASP Dependency-Check scan is the operational implementation of this lesson.

**Anthem breach (2015):** 78.8 million records, phishing credential theft, technical controls present, human layer underdeveloped. The direct validation that the phishing simulation program is not a nice-to-have metric but the human-layer complement to the technical controls.

**Ireland HSE ransomware (2021):** Phishing credential theft initial vector, extended clinical unavailability, national healthcare service affected. The most directly relevant case for why RS-004 was elevated to HIGH and why the CP-2 condition matters.

**Premera Blue Cross (2019):** Documented vulnerability, no remediation, breach, $6.8 million. The POA&M accountability lesson told through a real organizational failure.

**URMC settlement (2019):** Risk identified in risk analysis, implementation incomplete at Layers 3 and 4 of the compliance mapping. The four-layer traceability requirement validated by how OCR structures its investigations.

Each of these cases did more than illustrate a concept — they connected the abstract GRC framework to real organizations, real patients, and real consequences. That connection is what makes security work feel like security work rather than documentation compliance.

