## What This Portfolio Is For

This portfolio — 97 daily entries building a complete GRC program for OpenMRS on AWS — is designed to do one thing in a job interview or a hiring conversation: demonstrate that I can do the work, not just describe it.

Most GRC portfolios demonstrate framework knowledge. They show that the candidate understands what a risk register is, what a POA&M does, what HIPAA requires. That knowledge is necessary. It is not sufficient.

This portfolio demonstrates operational judgment — the specific decisions that cannot be reduced to framework application. Categorizing the system HIGH based on population-specific sensitivity rather than the standard FIPS 199 analysis. Choosing to document the AU-12 finding honestly with a note to future assessors rather than presenting it as fully compliant. Designing the IR-3 tabletop scenario specifically to find the gap in the IRP rather than to confirm that the IRP works. Framing the phishing simulation funding request around the HC3 threat intelligence rather than the abstract value of effectiveness metrics.

These judgment calls are what make the difference between a GRC analyst who can follow a framework and a GRC analyst who can run a security program. The 97-day project was designed to produce evidence of the latter.

